04496nam a22007095i 9780801460173DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014601737 a10.7591/97808014601732doi  a(DE-B1597)478237  a(OCoLC)979576285  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1147.E85bG37 2009eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a305.4094/090212221 aGarver, Valerie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen and Aristocratic Culture in the Carolingian World /cValerie Garver. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Women and Carolingian Society -- t1. Beauty: Appearance and Adornment -- t2. Family: Bonds and Memory -- t3. Prudence: Instruction and Moral Exemplarity -- t4. Wealth: Hospitality and Domestic Management -- t5. Textile Work -- tConclusion: The Lifecycle of Aristocratic Women -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the wealth of scholarship in recent decades on medieval women, we still know much less about the experiences of women in the early Middle Ages than we do about those in later centuries. In Women and Aristocratic Culture in the Carolingian World, Valerie L. Garver offers a fresh appraisal of the cultural and social history of eighth- and ninth-century women. Examining changes in women's lives and in the ways others perceived women during the early Middle Ages, she shows that lay and religious women, despite their legal and social constrictions, played integral roles in Carolingian society.Garver's innovative book employs an especially wide range of sources, both textual and material, which she uses to construct a more complex and nuanced impression of aristocratic women than we've seen before. She looks at the importance of female beauty and adornment; the family and the construction of identities and collective memory; education and moral exemplarity; wealth, hospitality and domestic management; textile work, and the lifecycle of elite Carolingian women.Her interdisciplinary approach makes deft use of canons of church councils, chronicles, charters, polyptychs, capitularies, letters, poetry, exegesis, liturgy, inventories, hagiography, memorial books, artworks, archaeological remains, and textiles. Ultimately, Women and Aristocratic Culture in the Carolingian World underlines the centrality of the Carolingian era to the reshaping of antique ideas and the development of lasting social norms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCarolingians. 0aSocial historyyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aUpper class womenzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomenzEuropexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146017340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460173423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460173/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK